<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="95" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
The species is morphologically most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. engleriana" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="engleriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. engleriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by its leaves which are pyriform and 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.0" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="10.0">10-14 mm</quantity>
long (vs. narrowly oblong and 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.0" unit="mm" value="22.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="20.0">20-25 mm</quantity>
long), its 4-flowered inflorescences (vs. 5-7-flowered), its calyx lobes ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
long (vs. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.5">1.5-2 mm</quantity>
long) and the triangular corolla (vs. narrowly oblong to oblong-triangular).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
